ice. Simultaneously a human figure and a theatrical mask, Pierrot elicits artistic reflection on the representation of personality in the marketplace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArtszFrancexHistory. 0aPierrot (Fictitious character). 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAdolphe Willette.  aAntoine Watteau.  aBric-a-brac.  aCommedia dell’arte.  aComédie Italienne.  aEnfants du Paradis.  aJacques Prévert.  aMarcel Carné.  aMarketplace.  aNadar.  aPhysiognomies.  aPierrot.  aTheatricality.  aUniversal Exhibition.  aearly film.  aearly photography.  apantomime.  atheatrical stock characters.1 aKnowles, Marika Takanishi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2024 eBook-Packagez9783111332345oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152617408640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526174086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526174086/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2024